so) an altered form of this or of the variant   Buri  . The surname <i>Burry</i> is very rare in Switzerland."],"variants":[{"name":"Burri","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Erna, Hans.","Swiss German: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  ).","Albanian: nickname from <i>burrë</i> (definite form <i>burri</i>) ‘man’, figuratively ‘brave man’, ‘man of his word’, and ‘distinguished person’."]}]},{"name":"Lanza","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Shortened form of   Alanna ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"di","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Diana   and   Diane ."],"variants":[{"name":"Diana","meanings":["Name borne in Roman mythology by the goddess of the moon and of hunting, equivalent to the Greek Artemis. In mythology she is characterized as both beautiful and chaste. Her name is of ancient and uncertain derivation. It probably contains a first element that is also found in the name of the Greek god <i>Dionysos</i> (  see  Dennis  ) and the Latin name of the supreme god <i>Jupiter</i>. It was adopted in Britain during the Tudor period as a learned name, a borrowing from Latin influenced by the French form   Diane .  Although it was much used by Elizabethan poets celebrating the virgin goddess and alluding to the Virgin Queen, it was not particularly popular as a given name until the end of the 19th century. In earlier centuries some clergymen were reluctant to baptize girls with this pagan name, mindful of the riots against St Paul stirred up by worshippers of Diana of the Ephesians (Acts 19:24–41). In the late 20th century, its popularity received a boost because of its association with the late  Diana , Princess of Wales (  1961–97 ), who was renowned for her beauty, glamour, and compassion."]},{"name":"Diane","meanings":["form of   Diana  , now also widely used in the English-speaking world. It was especially popular among the Renaissance aristocracy, who loved hunting and were therefore proud to name their daughters after the classical goddess of the chase."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lanza di Burro was born about 1168, in Milan, Lombardy, Italy. She had at least 1 son with Luigi Borri."},"et":{"about 1168–":"umbes 1168–Surnud","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1190":"1190","1168":"1168","1100":"1100","about 1168":"umbes 1168","1261":"1261","Milano, Lombardia, Itália":"Milano, Lombardia, Itaalia","Milan,Lombardy,Italy.":"Milano, Lombardia, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1168–":"noin 1168–Kuollut","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1168–Female":"1168–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1168":"1168","1100":"1100","about 1168":"noin 1168","1261":"1261","Milano, Lombardia, Itália":"Milano, Lombardia, Italia","Milan,Lombardy,Italy.":"Milano, Lombardia, Italia"},"fr":{"about 1168–":"environ 1168–Décédée","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1168–Female":"1168–Décédée","1190":"1190","1168":"1168","1100":"1100","about 1168":"environ 1168","1261":"1261","Milano, Lombardia, Itália":"Milano, Lombardia, Italie","Milan,Lombardy,Italy.":"Milano, Lombardia, Italie","lifeSummary":"Lanza di Burro est née environ 1168, à Milano, Lombardia, Italie. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Luigi Borri."},"de":{"about 1168–":"um 1168–Verstorben","1100–Male":"1100–Verstorben","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1168–Female":"1168–Verstorben","1190":"1190","1168":"1168","1100":"1100","about 1168":"um 1168","1261":"1261","Milano, Lombardia, Itália":"Milano, Lombardei, Italien","Milan,Lombardy,Italy.":"Milano, Lombardei, Italien","lifeSummary":"Lanza di Burro wurde um 1168 in Milano, Lombardei, Italien geboren. Sie hatte mit Luigi Borri mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1168–":"about 1168–Desede","1100–Male":"1100–Desede","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1168–Female":"1168–Desede","1190":